        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-06-04T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-06-04T15:00:00-05:00" n="812" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d812">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">501.BB Korea/6–448: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Political Adviser in Korea</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Jacobs</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d812fn1">Repeated as 118 to Canberra.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-06-04T16:00:00-04:00">June 4, 1948—4 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>172. In recent conversation with rep of Dept, Harry of Australian Emb stated: (1)
                    that his Govt is far from satisfied with handling of Korean elections; (2) that
                    there is considerable evidence of police pressure in connection therewith; (3)
                    that in his opinion <gloss target="#t_UNTCOK1">UNTCOK</gloss> may take position
                    that elections were only provincial and not national <pb facs="1230" n="1216" xml:id="pg_1216"/> in scope; and (4) that latter point will at least be made
                    in minority report of <gloss target="#t_UNTCOK1">UNTCOK</gloss>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Marshall</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
